column34: The flashcard app is fast to open, without distraction and easy to use. For most of interactions with quizbot, I need to wait ~2 seconds for the bot's response and click on an option suggested by the bot. However, the flashcard app saves these '2 secs' for me which I think is REALLY efficient. I just tap a button to see hint, see answer and change subject. It's not that easy using quizbot if I wanted to know the answer of a question without attempting to answer it, or even the explanation of answers as soon as I see the question.
column39: Choosing from choices is much more effective
column41: How can you evaluate the graphical design of a bot... I don't like any images or even any emoji when I'm chatting with someone because they don't explicitly express your feelings. Especially for a bot targeting test-preparing people, images and emojis are just distractions. I don't want any graphical design from a bot. Please just give me words.
column43: The NLP backend is pretty good for safety questions, but not that good for GRE questions as I use it. I also want more flexible conversation patterns, like change subjects as soon as I see a boring question by typing "change subject", which is not currently supported. Currently it seems like I can only change subject after I finishes answering a question.
column46: They're not the same thing at all. I say Ok Google when I'm driving and I need a gas station along the route. The reason I need it is because my hands are not available. If I have any chance to type using keyboard, I'll never talk to a virtual assistant because it's more precise and it saves time. I even don't want to use the mouse at all if I can do the same thing with a keyboard because it saves time. QuizBot is better in this case because I can type words instead of speaking to it. But honestly, since all functions of a quizbot is also there on flashcard app, it doesn't make much sense to use a chatbot which is not as efficient as flashcard app (because I have limited choices and have to wait for replies). But one thing that quizbot is absolutely useful is analyzing users' input and match that with correct answer. That's something a simple flashcard won't do. But that might require a better NLP backend.
